xtensive use of previously untapped FBI files as well as overlooked materials in the Library of Congress's Bernstein archive, Seldes illuminates the ways in which Bernstein's career intersected with the twentieth century's most momentous events. This broadly accessible and impressively documented account of the celebrity-maestro's life deepens our understanding of an entire era as it reveals important and often ignored intersections of American culture and political power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusiciansxPolitical activityzUnited States. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aamerican culture.  aamerican history.  aartists.  abiography.  ablacklisted.  acareer.  aclassical music.  acold war america.  acomposer.  aengaging.  aexile.  afamous musicians.  afbi files.  afolk heroes.  aiconic musicians.  aleonard bernstein.  alibrary of congress.  amaestro.  amodern history.  amusic lovers.  amusical career.  amusical theater.  anew york philharmonic.  anew york.  anonfiction.  apolitical activist.  apolitical outcasts.  apopular culture.  aprogressive politics.  aretrospective.  arevolutionaries.  astate department.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025764140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094307040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943070/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY